'''Mattias Olof Svanberg''' (born 5 January 1999) is a Swedish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[2. Bundesliga]] club [[VfL Wolfsburg]] and the [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden national team]].

==Club career==

===Malmo FF===
After playing for [[IF Limhamn Bunkeflo (men's)|LB07]] and [[Malmö FF]] youth teams Mattias Svanberg signed an apprenticeship contract with Malmö FF on 27 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mff.se/aktuellt/nyheter/Nyheter/2015-07-27_mff_skriver_larlingskontrakt_med_mattias_svanberg | title=MFF skriver lärlingskontrakt med Mattias Svanberg | publisher=Malmö FF | work=mff.se | date=27 July 2015 | access-date=28 May 2016 | language=Swedish | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003081540/http://www.mff.se/aktuellt/nyheter/Nyheter/2015-07-27_mff_skriver_larlingskontrakt_med_mattias_svanberg | archive-date=3 October 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> As a 16-year-old, he featured on the bench four times during the [[2015 Allsvenskan|2015 season]]. On 4 March 2016, he signed a four-year first team contract with Malmö.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mff.se/sv-SE/aktuellt/nyheter/Nyheter/2016-03-04_svanberg-skriver-pa-for-fyra-ar-med-mff | title=MFF skriver A-kontrakt med Svanberg | publisher=Malmö FF | work=mff.se | date=4 March 2016 | access-date=28 May 2016 | language=Swedish | archive-date=8 July 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708191928/http://www.mff.se/sv-SE/aktuellt/nyheter/Nyheter/2016-03-04_svanberg-skriver-pa-for-fyra-ar-med-mff | url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his [[Allsvenskan]] debut on 28 May 2016 when he came on as a substitute in the 82nd minute in a 4–1 win against [[Östersunds FK]], and assisted on [[Viðar Örn Kjartansson]]'s goal in stoppage time. On 25 September 2016, he scored his first Allsvenskan goal in the [[Helsingborgs IF–Malmö FF rivalry|local derby]] against [[Helsingborgs IF]]. He started his first game for the club on 26 October 2016, and scored a goal and an assist as Malmö FF beat [[Falkenbergs FF]] to secure the [[2016 Allsvenskan|Allsvenskan]] title.

===Bologna===
In [[2017 Allsvenskan|2017]], Svanberg received a larger role with the team and made 21 appearances as MFF won the championship for a second consecutive year. In [[2018 Allsvenskan|2018]], Svanberg became a consistent starter and was one of only two players to feature in every match during the spring before moving to [[Serie A]] club [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in the summer transfer window for a sum of €5 million.

He made his Serie A debut on 16 September 2018 in a 0–1 defeat against [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]].

===Wolfsburg===
On 16 July 2022, [[Bundesliga]] club [[VfL Wolfsburg]] announced the signing of Svanberg on a five-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Svanberg signs |url=https://www.vfl-wolfsburg.de/en/newsdetails/news-detail/detail/news/svanberg-signs |access-date=2022-07-16 |website=www.vfl-wolfsburg.de |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Svanberg was called up to the senior [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] squad for games against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] and [[Russia national football team|Russia]] in November 2018, but did not play.<ref>{{cite news|title=Svanberg receives first Sweden call-up |url=https://www.bolognafc.it/en/svanberg-receives-first-sweden-call-up/ |access-date=3 September 2019|website=bolognafc.it |date=12 November 2018}}</ref>

In November 2019, Svanberg was called up for Sweden's [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualification]] matches against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Dejan Kulusevski och Mattias Svanberg med i EM-kvaltruppen|url=https://www.expressen.se/tv/sport/fotboll/landslaget/dubbla-skrallar-i-em-kvaltruppen/|access-date=2020-08-26|website=Expressen TV|date=6 November 2019 |language=sv}}</ref> On 18 November Svanberg scored on his debut against Faroe Islands at [[Friends Arena]] in [[Solna]]. He also assisted [[John Guidetti]] in a 3–0 win for the home side.<ref>{{Cite web|title=TV: Drömdebut för Mattias Svanberg i landslaget – nätade mot Färöarna|url=https://www.fotbollskanalen.se/sverige/tv-dromdebut-for-mattias-svanberg-i-landslaget---natade-mot-faroarna/|access-date=2020-08-26|website=fotbollskanalen|language=sv}}</ref>

Svanberg was called up for a major tournament for the first time when he was included in Sweden's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sweden Euro 2020 squad: Full team profile |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/sweden-euro-2020-squad-the-complete-line-up-for-marchs-internationals |website=[[FourFourTwo]] |date=14 June 2021 |access-date=14 June 2021 |ref=euro2020squad}}</ref>

On 12 May 2026, Svanberg was named in the Sweden squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-12 |title=Mystiskt inlägg efter petningen |url=https://www.expressen.se/sport/fotboll/landslaget/har-ar-sveriges-trupp-till-fotbolls-vm-2026/ |access-date=2026-05-15 |website=www.expressen.se |language=sv}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Svanberg is the son of the former professional [[ice hockey]] player [[Bo Svanberg]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Guldfamiljen: "Är så stolt över honom nu"|url=https://www.expressen.se/kvallsposten/sport/guldfamiljen-ar-sa-stolt-over-honom-nu/|access-date=2020-08-26|website=www.expressen.se|date=27 October 2016 |language=sv}}</ref>

